WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.980 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:04.980 --> 00:00:33.420 align:middle line:90%


00:00:33.420 --> 00:00:37.400 align:middle line:84%
>> We need to find new
ways of living together,

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:41.130 align:middle line:84%
and that is what I'm
looking for in my work.

00:00:41.130 --> 00:00:46.530 align:middle line:84%
>> I still believe bettering
the world and society through

00:00:46.530 --> 00:00:48.030 align:middle line:90%
technology.

00:00:48.030 --> 00:00:50.970 align:middle line:84%
>> I think the economy is one
reason why people are trying

00:00:50.970 --> 00:00:55.280 align:middle line:84%
to downsize, because
things are so expensive.

00:00:55.280 --> 00:00:57.380 align:middle line:84%
>> You use
already-manufactured objects,

00:00:57.380 --> 00:01:00.040 align:middle line:84%
then you bring it
into the architecture.

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:02.340 align:middle line:84%
So it's like ready
made in architecture.

00:01:02.340 --> 00:01:05.660 align:middle line:84%
>> A lot of people just don't
like the fact that they've been

00:01:05.660 --> 00:01:08.420 align:middle line:84%
essentially forced into larger
spaces than they actually want

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:09.680 align:middle line:90%
to be in.

00:01:09.680 --> 00:01:13.420 align:middle line:84%
>> We have to re-appropriate
existing things,

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:17.250 align:middle line:84%
make new items out
of this garbage.

00:01:17.250 --> 00:01:19.880 align:middle line:84%
>> There's no question in my
mind that something that is

00:01:19.880 --> 00:01:23.990 align:middle line:84%
more compact is a
smarter way to build.

00:01:23.990 --> 00:01:26.960 align:middle line:84%
>> Now what we can do is we
can use all of this trash,

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:29.480 align:middle line:84%
which is damaging the ecology,
and turn it into something

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:31.302 align:middle line:90%
really beneficial.

00:01:31.302 --> 00:01:33.260 align:middle line:84%
>> I think I'm trying to
create a better world,

00:01:33.260 --> 00:01:36.440 align:middle line:84%
and in order to do that, we have
to experiment and try out other

00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:37.810 align:middle line:90%
ways of living.

00:01:37.810 --> 00:02:02.300 align:middle line:90%


00:02:02.300 --> 00:02:06.440 align:middle line:84%
>> I find it very interesting
to look at something and imagine

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:08.104 align:middle line:90%
what its next life would become.

00:02:08.104 --> 00:02:11.920 align:middle line:90%


00:02:11.920 --> 00:02:14.560 align:middle line:84%
Given my interest
in mobility, I've

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:17.830 align:middle line:84%
always looked at
structures that are outside

00:02:17.830 --> 00:02:21.550 align:middle line:90%
of architecture that move.

00:02:21.550 --> 00:02:25.520 align:middle line:84%
Part of my thinking has to do
with the nature of being human,

00:02:25.520 --> 00:02:28.210 align:middle line:90%
and what does that entail.

00:02:28.210 --> 00:02:32.860 align:middle line:84%
To some degree, we have
this desire to hold memory.

00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:36.910 align:middle line:84%
And often our memories
are stored in our attics,

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:40.720 align:middle line:84%
because they're embedded
within the objects that we own.

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:43.810 align:middle line:84%
But now memory can just
be stored on a hard drive.

00:02:43.810 --> 00:02:49.820 align:middle line:84%
So we can dispose or do away
with the collection of stuff

00:02:49.820 --> 00:02:53.245 align:middle line:90%
and live more lightly.

00:02:53.245 --> 00:02:58.220 align:middle line:90%


00:02:58.220 --> 00:03:04.350 align:middle line:84%
As humans, I really feel like we
were not meant to be sedentary.

00:03:04.350 --> 00:03:06.660 align:middle line:84%
Constantly when I
travel, I'm always

00:03:06.660 --> 00:03:09.240 align:middle line:84%
drawn to the people
that are building

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:12.570 align:middle line:84%
with makeshift
construction pieces,

00:03:12.570 --> 00:03:16.350 align:middle line:90%
or using wheels in unusual ways.

00:03:16.350 --> 00:03:20.220 align:middle line:84%
And I looked further
and further into that,

00:03:20.220 --> 00:03:22.560 align:middle line:84%
and found that there's
an incredible history

00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:28.500 align:middle line:84%
of mobile lifestyles,
and it became my passion.

00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:31.800 align:middle line:90%


00:03:31.800 --> 00:03:34.530 align:middle line:84%
Recently I took an
old truck trailer

00:03:34.530 --> 00:03:39.210 align:middle line:84%
and craned it in over my house
and attached it to the back--

00:03:39.210 --> 00:03:43.260 align:middle line:84%
a structure that might
not be roadworthy anymore,

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:47.760 align:middle line:84%
and rethought how I could skin
it, how I could create openings

00:03:47.760 --> 00:03:52.440 align:middle line:84%
in it, and make a contribution
to a dwelling that

00:03:52.440 --> 00:03:56.310 align:middle line:84%
then could also be moved
and relocated as needed.

00:03:56.310 --> 00:04:10.210 align:middle line:90%


00:04:10.210 --> 00:04:13.060 align:middle line:84%
I get really excited when
I'm driving down the freeway

00:04:13.060 --> 00:04:15.100 align:middle line:90%
and I see a truck go by.

00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:17.500 align:middle line:84%
And I immediately
start to fantasize

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:20.620 align:middle line:84%
about how that could
become part of a house,

00:04:20.620 --> 00:04:23.995 align:middle line:84%
or it could become
a mobile library.

00:04:23.995 --> 00:04:27.480 align:middle line:90%


00:04:27.480 --> 00:04:30.510 align:middle line:84%
There's a tremendous amount
of industrial materials

00:04:30.510 --> 00:04:34.950 align:middle line:84%
that are out in the landscape
that can be redeployed

00:04:34.950 --> 00:04:36.902 align:middle line:90%
in a variety of different ways.

00:04:36.902 --> 00:04:38.360 align:middle line:84%
For example, the
shipping container

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:41.430 align:middle line:90%
is a terrific example.

00:04:41.430 --> 00:04:45.180 align:middle line:84%
I'm not spending energy on
creating it from scratch,

00:04:45.180 --> 00:04:48.600 align:middle line:84%
but I'm repurposing
it for another use.

00:04:48.600 --> 00:04:57.930 align:middle line:90%


00:04:57.930 --> 00:05:02.540 align:middle line:84%
The Joshua Tree prefab
is a modular home,

00:05:02.540 --> 00:05:09.050 align:middle line:84%
sits out on the desert floor,
and is a fully self-sufficient

00:05:09.050 --> 00:05:13.790 align:middle line:84%
structure, where it is not
attached to the electrical grid

00:05:13.790 --> 00:05:18.020 align:middle line:84%
and is not attached
to the water system.

00:05:18.020 --> 00:05:21.620 align:middle line:84%
It is a very simple
building that is really

00:05:21.620 --> 00:05:28.430 align:middle line:84%
meant to allow you to
sleep, to eat, and to relax,

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:31.780 align:middle line:84%
that then can be moved
from location to location

00:05:31.780 --> 00:05:33.040 align:middle line:90%
at the snap of a finger.

00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:40.210 align:middle line:90%


00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:42.460 align:middle line:84%
I would say that
there absolutely

00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:48.010 align:middle line:84%
is a movement that is pervasive
throughout this country, where

00:05:48.010 --> 00:05:50.860 align:middle line:84%
people are looking
to be able to create

00:05:50.860 --> 00:05:56.080 align:middle line:84%
their environments without
having rules thrust upon them.

00:05:56.080 --> 00:06:00.740 align:middle line:84%
Within that thinking, there is
a difference in terms of scale.

00:06:00.740 --> 00:06:05.110 align:middle line:84%
So it's less about bigger
is better, and more

00:06:05.110 --> 00:06:07.120 align:middle line:90%
about smaller is smarter.

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:10.590 align:middle line:90%


00:06:10.590 --> 00:06:13.620 align:middle line:84%
And that is connected
to the dwelling

00:06:13.620 --> 00:06:15.960 align:middle line:90%
that we have around us.

00:06:15.960 --> 00:06:19.995 align:middle line:84%
So the less stuff we have, the
lighter that the materials are,

00:06:19.995 --> 00:06:23.490 align:middle line:84%
the smarter they
become, the less

00:06:23.490 --> 00:06:25.680 align:middle line:90%
encumbered we become as people.

00:06:25.680 --> 00:06:30.790 align:middle line:90%


00:06:30.790 --> 00:06:33.440 align:middle line:84%
The buildings that I
create are not large,

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:36.810 align:middle line:84%
and yet they have a
sense of volume to them.

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:38.450 align:middle line:90%
They have natural light.

00:06:38.450 --> 00:06:41.450 align:middle line:84%
They have ceilings
that tend to be higher

00:06:41.450 --> 00:06:46.730 align:middle line:84%
than conventional houses
so that you feel expansive

00:06:46.730 --> 00:06:49.490 align:middle line:84%
in terms of height, but not
necessarily in terms of width.

00:06:49.490 --> 00:06:56.110 align:middle line:90%


00:06:56.110 --> 00:06:59.110 align:middle line:84%
If you can look outside
and be connected

00:06:59.110 --> 00:07:01.660 align:middle line:84%
to the natural
environment outside,

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:05.920 align:middle line:84%
you are expanding
your space visually,

00:07:05.920 --> 00:07:07.510 align:middle line:90%
but not necessarily physically.

00:07:07.510 --> 00:07:14.150 align:middle line:90%


00:07:14.150 --> 00:07:17.630 align:middle line:84%
Innately as a human being, we
are nomadic and we're mobile

00:07:17.630 --> 00:07:23.390 align:middle line:84%
and we're curious, and we
will always be exploring.

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:26.260 align:middle line:84%
Whether it's here in the
desert, or whether it's

00:07:26.260 --> 00:07:32.290 align:middle line:84%
out in space, or in the ocean,
we can't just let that go.

00:07:32.290 --> 00:07:51.120 align:middle line:90%


00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:53.220 align:middle line:84%
>> When I look at what I
consider to be beautiful

00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:55.770 align:middle line:84%
in the world, it's
what is necessary.

00:07:55.770 --> 00:07:58.800 align:middle line:84%
When something is truly
necessary, it becomes vital,

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:01.455 align:middle line:84%
and it seems important,
and it seems beautiful.

00:08:01.455 --> 00:08:08.390 align:middle line:90%


00:08:08.390 --> 00:08:10.040 align:middle line:84%
The average American
house puts out

00:08:10.040 --> 00:08:13.760 align:middle line:84%
like 18 tons worth of
greenhouse gases per year,

00:08:13.760 --> 00:08:16.010 align:middle line:84%
consumes about a quarter
acre of woodland,

00:08:16.010 --> 00:08:18.680 align:middle line:84%
puts another seven tons
of construction waste

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:20.070 align:middle line:90%
into the local landfill.

00:08:20.070 --> 00:08:25.370 align:middle line:84%
So I wanted to contribute to
that as little as I had to

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:28.214 align:middle line:84%
and still have a
great place to live.

00:08:28.214 --> 00:08:31.553 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:08:31.553 --> 00:08:34.630 align:middle line:90%


00:08:34.630 --> 00:08:39.970 align:middle line:84%
I never did any building
until I decided to live small.

00:08:39.970 --> 00:08:42.640 align:middle line:84%
And I couldn't really afford to
have anybody else build for me.

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:45.740 align:middle line:84%
So I built my own house, and
that's how I learned to do it,

00:08:45.740 --> 00:08:46.540 align:middle line:90%
just by doing.

00:08:46.540 --> 00:08:50.990 align:middle line:90%


00:08:50.990 --> 00:08:55.400 align:middle line:84%
I've actually lived in four
tiny houses of about this size.

00:08:55.400 --> 00:08:57.750 align:middle line:84%
The first one was pretty
much exactly this size.

00:08:57.750 --> 00:08:59.030 align:middle line:90%
The second one--

00:08:59.030 --> 00:09:01.662 align:middle line:84%
When I moved to California where
the land prices are expensive,

00:09:01.662 --> 00:09:03.620 align:middle line:84%
I wanted to make sure my
house was small enough

00:09:03.620 --> 00:09:05.990 align:middle line:84%
that I could parallel
park it by hand

00:09:05.990 --> 00:09:08.502 align:middle line:90%
if I had to live on the street.

00:09:08.502 --> 00:09:10.460 align:middle line:84%
Turned out I didn't have
to live on the street.

00:09:10.460 --> 00:09:15.500 align:middle line:84%
So I sold that one and
built another, larger one,

00:09:15.500 --> 00:09:16.730 align:middle line:90%
and then, finally, this one.

00:09:16.730 --> 00:09:20.470 align:middle line:90%


00:09:20.470 --> 00:09:23.680 align:middle line:84%
The first step to designing
a very small efficient space

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:26.740 align:middle line:84%
seems to be figuring out
what you actually need,

00:09:26.740 --> 00:09:29.270 align:middle line:84%
and then getting
rid of everything.

00:09:29.270 --> 00:09:31.790 align:middle line:84%
So in my case, for example, I
don't cook very much at all.

00:09:31.790 --> 00:09:34.660 align:middle line:84%
So my counter's only three
and a half feet long.

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:37.680 align:middle line:84%
If I cooked a lot, I might turn
the whole house into a kitchen.

00:09:37.680 --> 00:09:39.130 align:middle line:84%
But it's a matter
of deciding what

00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:42.910 align:middle line:84%
you need to do to be happy, and
then accommodating for that.

00:09:42.910 --> 00:09:44.010 align:middle line:90%
Because if you're not--

00:09:44.010 --> 00:09:48.670 align:middle line:84%
I guess the other side of living
simply is living too simply,

00:09:48.670 --> 00:09:51.580 align:middle line:84%
perhaps, and not having what you
need, which isn't good either.

00:09:51.580 --> 00:09:59.570 align:middle line:90%


00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:04.560 align:middle line:84%
The laws in the US say you can't
build a house that's too small.

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:07.370 align:middle line:84%
There are a few different
rules in there that apply.

00:10:07.370 --> 00:10:09.770 align:middle line:84%
You've got to have a
room of 120 square feet.

00:10:09.770 --> 00:10:11.990 align:middle line:84%
Any bedroom has to be
at least 70 square feet.

00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:14.630 align:middle line:84%
When you add it all up, it's
bigger than I actually wanted.

00:10:14.630 --> 00:10:17.350 align:middle line:90%


00:10:17.350 --> 00:10:22.000 align:middle line:84%
So by putting a house on wheels,
it's no longer a building,

00:10:22.000 --> 00:10:25.660 align:middle line:84%
doesn't have to abide
by building codes,

00:10:25.660 --> 00:10:28.330 align:middle line:84%
and you can build it
as small as you want.

00:10:28.330 --> 00:10:30.652 align:middle line:84%
You just can't go too big,
because otherwise you're

00:10:30.652 --> 00:10:32.110 align:middle line:84%
probably going to
hit a bridge when

00:10:32.110 --> 00:10:33.318 align:middle line:90%
you're driving down the road.

00:10:33.318 --> 00:10:40.110 align:middle line:90%


00:10:40.110 --> 00:10:42.030 align:middle line:84%
It is sort of a
counter-cultural thing.

00:10:42.030 --> 00:10:45.420 align:middle line:84%
I think a lot of people
just don't like the fact

00:10:45.420 --> 00:10:47.790 align:middle line:84%
that they've been essentially
forced into larger spaces

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:49.890 align:middle line:84%
than they actually
want to be in.

00:10:49.890 --> 00:10:55.230 align:middle line:84%
So besides just being
environmental and economic,

00:10:55.230 --> 00:10:58.260 align:middle line:84%
this whole thing is also sort
of a civil disobedience act.

00:10:58.260 --> 00:11:02.470 align:middle line:90%


00:11:02.470 --> 00:11:07.660 align:middle line:84%
It's a way of getting around the
forces that have forced people

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:09.670 align:middle line:84%
into more house than
they actually wanted

00:11:09.670 --> 00:11:10.780 align:middle line:90%
or needed in the past.

00:11:10.780 --> 00:11:14.980 align:middle line:90%


00:11:14.980 --> 00:11:18.388 align:middle line:84%
I hope to build a village
within the next couple of years

00:11:18.388 --> 00:11:19.930 align:middle line:84%
in this county so
people don't always

00:11:19.930 --> 00:11:22.450 align:middle line:84%
have to fight the codes
and the zoning laws.

00:11:22.450 --> 00:11:24.160 align:middle line:84%
They can just live
in a tiny house

00:11:24.160 --> 00:11:27.460 align:middle line:84%
village, which will probably
be zoned as a trailer park,

00:11:27.460 --> 00:11:28.450 align:middle line:90%
oddly enough.

00:11:28.450 --> 00:11:30.610 align:middle line:84%
I've never really
thought of myself

00:11:30.610 --> 00:11:32.860 align:middle line:84%
as a trailer park
type of person,

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:35.270 align:middle line:84%
but this won't be your
average trailer park.

00:11:35.270 --> 00:11:39.190 align:middle line:84%
It'll be lots of pedestrian
walkways, cars out back,

00:11:39.190 --> 00:11:42.250 align:middle line:84%
and it will basically
be co-housing

00:11:42.250 --> 00:11:44.290 align:middle line:90%
for the anti-social--

00:11:44.290 --> 00:11:47.227 align:middle line:84%
like shared some things,
but lots of privacy

00:11:47.227 --> 00:11:48.310 align:middle line:90%
in your little houses too.

00:11:48.310 --> 00:11:53.730 align:middle line:90%


00:11:53.730 --> 00:11:57.670 align:middle line:84%
I can fit a bed downstairs,
but if I put a bed downstairs,

00:11:57.670 --> 00:11:58.470 align:middle line:90%
I don't have--

00:11:58.470 --> 00:12:00.012 align:middle line:84%
I mean, that takes
up a lot of space.

00:12:00.012 --> 00:12:02.520 align:middle line:90%
So I just go up.

00:12:02.520 --> 00:12:06.600 align:middle line:84%
I like to use vertical space
as much as possible to make

00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:07.963 align:middle line:90%
things really efficient.

00:12:07.963 --> 00:12:21.290 align:middle line:90%


00:12:21.290 --> 00:12:23.820 align:middle line:84%
A house in which there's
a lot of wasted space

00:12:23.820 --> 00:12:25.580 align:middle line:90%
just doesn't feel vital.

00:12:25.580 --> 00:12:28.080 align:middle line:84%
And you fill it with a bunch
of stuff you don't really need.

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:30.640 align:middle line:84%
Life itself seems
diminished a bit.

00:12:30.640 --> 00:12:33.360 align:middle line:84%
So in a house where
everything is necessary, life

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:35.710 align:middle line:90%
itself seems very necessary.

00:12:35.710 --> 00:12:38.250 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, I feel very much
more alive in a small place.

00:12:38.250 --> 00:12:49.300 align:middle line:90%


00:12:49.300 --> 00:12:50.760 align:middle line:90%
[NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:12:50.760 --> 00:13:07.160 align:middle line:90%


00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:09.950 align:middle line:84%
>> The reason why I'm
doing this project is

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:13.010 align:middle line:84%
because it's something that
I believe that is really

00:13:13.010 --> 00:13:17.240 align:middle line:84%
necessary with the way that
civilization is growing over

00:13:17.240 --> 00:13:20.990 align:middle line:84%
the planet, and it's
something that can really heal

00:13:20.990 --> 00:13:22.480 align:middle line:90%
the ecology of the planet.

00:13:22.480 --> 00:13:28.500 align:middle line:90%


00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:30.480 align:middle line:84%
Coming from a town in
the north of England

00:13:30.480 --> 00:13:33.450 align:middle line:84%
where there's quite a bit of
pollution, a lot of industry,

00:13:33.450 --> 00:13:37.980 align:middle line:84%
I was always quite interested
in ecology from an early age.

00:13:37.980 --> 00:13:42.150 align:middle line:90%


00:13:42.150 --> 00:13:45.690 align:middle line:84%
This idea came over a number
of years when I was in my 30s

00:13:45.690 --> 00:13:48.750 align:middle line:84%
after thinking deeply about
spiritual things, and also

00:13:48.750 --> 00:13:52.200 align:middle line:84%
ecological state of the planet
and what the future could

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:54.120 align:middle line:84%
be, with more
people all the time

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:56.280 align:middle line:84%
and more trees getting
cut down, this idea

00:13:56.280 --> 00:13:59.430 align:middle line:84%
came to actually grow
plants and use the trash

00:13:59.430 --> 00:14:04.050 align:middle line:84%
to create a base for a
floating garden that just keeps

00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:07.024 align:middle line:90%
getting stronger with time.

00:14:07.024 --> 00:14:10.496 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:14:10.496 --> 00:14:20.440 align:middle line:90%


00:14:20.440 --> 00:14:23.960 align:middle line:84%
Making land out of
plastic bottles and trash,

00:14:23.960 --> 00:14:27.870 align:middle line:84%
and this whole island with the
house included is about 70%

00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:29.090 align:middle line:90%
recycled.

00:14:29.090 --> 00:14:31.300 align:middle line:84%
So I've got really quite
a comfortable home.

00:14:31.300 --> 00:14:38.680 align:middle line:90%


00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:42.250 align:middle line:84%
The way I begin to build the
island, it's just so simple.

00:14:42.250 --> 00:14:44.800 align:middle line:84%
You take one shipping
pallet, and then

00:14:44.800 --> 00:14:49.840 align:middle line:84%
you get the bags of bottles and
just put them on the back end

00:14:49.840 --> 00:14:50.960 align:middle line:90%
and tie them together.

00:14:50.960 --> 00:15:13.000 align:middle line:90%


00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.140 align:middle line:84%
When a plastic bottle is
underneath a floating island

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:19.930 align:middle line:84%
in cool water where the
sun isn't getting on it,

00:15:19.930 --> 00:15:21.830 align:middle line:84%
it could last for
thousands of years.

00:15:21.830 --> 00:15:24.250 align:middle line:84%
We don't really know, but we
do know it last a lot longer.

00:15:24.250 --> 00:15:28.120 align:middle line:84%
And I actually took a
bag out after many years

00:15:28.120 --> 00:15:30.040 align:middle line:84%
of-- because I've been
doing this five years.

00:15:30.040 --> 00:15:33.970 align:middle line:84%
And so I've checked, and corals
are growing underneath on them.

00:15:33.970 --> 00:15:35.860 align:middle line:90%
And the tops get corals.

00:15:35.860 --> 00:15:38.380 align:middle line:84%
So you can't even take
the tops off afterwards.

00:15:38.380 --> 00:15:42.000 align:middle line:90%


00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.080 align:middle line:84%
And the idea is that it can get
big enough and strong enough

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:49.710 align:middle line:84%
to actually go on the ocean
and float down, and eventually

00:15:49.710 --> 00:15:52.525 align:middle line:84%
go through the Panama Canal
and out onto the Pacific.

00:15:52.525 --> 00:16:13.210 align:middle line:90%


00:16:13.210 --> 00:16:14.900 align:middle line:90%
It's not like a boat.

00:16:14.900 --> 00:16:19.120 align:middle line:84%
Boats are solid and
they rock like this,

00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:20.450 align:middle line:90%
and it's a different thing.

00:16:20.450 --> 00:16:22.940 align:middle line:84%
An island, because
it's all flexible,

00:16:22.940 --> 00:16:24.350 align:middle line:90%
the wave comes through.

00:16:24.350 --> 00:16:27.170 align:middle line:90%
So the island actually rolls.

00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:29.950 align:middle line:84%
So I say boats rock,
but islands roll.

00:16:29.950 --> 00:16:35.470 align:middle line:90%


00:16:35.470 --> 00:16:38.620 align:middle line:84%
There's many ways to
use and recycle and make

00:16:38.620 --> 00:16:39.640 align:middle line:90%
wonderful homes.

00:16:39.640 --> 00:16:42.940 align:middle line:84%
